---
import BlogLayout from '../../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
const faq = [
  { q: `Why does Japanese need counters?`, a: `Japanese does not have singular/plural forms. Counters specify the type and quantity of what you are counting, similar to English "a sheet of paper" or "a head of cattle." They tell the listener what kind of object is being counted.` },
  { q: `What if I use the wrong counter?`, a: `Using the generic counter つ (hitotsu, futatsu...) is always acceptable for most objects. Japanese people will understand you even with the wrong specific counter. As you progress, learning the correct counter shows fluency and attention to detail.` },
  { q: `How many counters do I need to know?`, a: `About 10–15 common counters cover 90% of daily situations. There are hundreds of specialized counters, but most Japanese people only regularly use 20–30. Focus on the essential ones first and add specialized counters as you encounter them.` },
  { q: `Why do counter readings change with certain numbers?`, a: `Sound changes (音便 onbin) occur to make pronunciation smoother. For example, いっぴき instead of いちひき is easier to say quickly. These follow consistent patterns based on whether the counter starts with h, k, s, or t sounds.` },
  { q: `Do I need counters for JLPT?`, a: `Yes — counters appear on every JLPT level. N5 tests basic counters (人, 枚, 本). N4-N3 add more specific counters. N2-N1 include uncommon counters in reading passages. Mastering counters is essential for the test and real-life Japanese.` }
];
const relatedTools = [
  { name: "JLPT Vocabulary", url: "/japanese/tools/jlpt-vocabulary/" },
  { name: "Number Converter", url: "/japanese/tools/number-converter/" },
  { name: "Kanji Lookup", url: "/japanese/tools/kanji-lookup/" }
];
const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: "why-counters", text: "Why Counters Exist in Japanese" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "generic-counter", text: "The Generic Counter つ — Your Safety Net" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "essential-counters", text: "10 Essential Counters for Daily Life" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "sound-changes", text: "Sound Change Rules — The Tricky Part" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "time-counters", text: "Time and Date Counters" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "specialized-counters", text: "Specialized Counters Worth Knowing" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "common-mistakes", text: "Common Counter Mistakes and How to Fix Them" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "practice-tips", text: "How to Practice and Remember Counters" }
];
---
<BlogLayout
  title="Japanese Counters: Complete Guide to Counting Everything Correctly"
  description="Master Japanese counters with this complete guide. Learn the 10 essential counters, sound change rules, time counters, and practical tips for daily use and JLPT preparation."
  language="japanese"
  category="grammar"
  tags={["vocabulary", "grammar", "beginner", "counters", "jlpt"]}
  publishDate="2026-02-25"
  image="https://images.pexels.com/photos/5412226/pexels-photo-5412226.jpeg?auto=compress&cs=tinysrgb&dpr=2&h=650&w=940"
  imageAlt="Bright plastic numbers on a blue background with ample copy space, ideal for educational themes."
  faq={faq}
  relatedTools={relatedTools}
  headings={headings}
>

<h2 id="why-counters">Why Counters Exist in Japanese</h2>
  <p>In English, you can simply say "three books" or "five cats." In Japanese, you need a <strong>counter word</strong> (助数詞 josūshi) between the number and the noun — or after the noun with the particle を. Counters classify objects by their shape, size, or type, telling the listener <em>what kind of thing</em> is being counted.</p>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fca5a5; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #dc2626;">❌ Without Counter</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0.5rem 0;">三犬 (san inu) — unnatural / incorrect</p>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #f0fdf4; border: 1px solid #86efac; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong style="color: #16a34a;">✅ With Counter</strong>
      <p style="font-size: 0.95rem; margin: 0.5rem 0;">犬三匹 (inu sanbiki) — three dogs ✓</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <p>Think of it like English measure words: you say "two <em>slices</em> of pizza" not "two pizzas of slice." Japanese simply uses this system for <em>everything</em> — people, animals, flat things, long things, machines, and more.</p>

  <h2 id="generic-counter">The Generic Counter つ — Your Safety Net</h2>
  <p>Before learning specific counters, memorize the <strong>generic counter つ</strong> (tsu). It works for most small objects and is always understood, even when a specific counter exists. This is your lifeline when you cannot remember the right counter.</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #7c3aed; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Number</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Japanese</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Reading</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Number</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Japanese</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Reading</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;">1</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">一つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ひとつ (hitotsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">6</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">六つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">むっつ (muttsu)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;">2</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">二つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ふたつ (futatsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">7</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">七つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ななつ (nanatsu)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;">3</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">三つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">みっつ (mittsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">8</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">八つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">やっつ (yattsu)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;">4</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">四つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">よっつ (yottsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">9</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">九つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ここのつ (kokonotsu)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;">5</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">五つ</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">いつつ (itsutsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">10</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;">十</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">とお (tō)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div style="background: #fefce8; border-left: 4px solid #eab308; padding: 1rem 1.2rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <strong>⚠️ Limitation:</strong> The つ counter only goes up to 10 and cannot be used for people (use 人) or very specific categories. For numbers above 10, you need the specific counter.
  </div>

  <h2 id="essential-counters">10 Essential Counters for Daily Life</h2>
  <p>These 10 counters cover approximately 90% of daily counting situations. Master these first before learning specialized counters:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #1e40af; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Counter</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Reading</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Used For</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Examples</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">"3" Example</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>人</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">にん (nin)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">People</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Friends, family, students</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三人 (さんにん)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>枚</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">まい (mai)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Flat, thin objects</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Paper, tickets, plates, shirts</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三枚 (さんまい)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>本</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ほん (hon)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Long, cylindrical objects</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Pens, bottles, trees, roads, movies</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三本 (さんぼん)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>匹</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ひき (hiki)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Small/medium animals</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Cats, dogs, fish, insects</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三匹 (さんびき)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>冊</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">さつ (satsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Books, notebooks</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Books, magazines, notebooks</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三冊 (さんさつ)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>台</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">だい (dai)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Machines, vehicles</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Cars, computers, TVs, bikes</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三台 (さんだい)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>個</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">こ (ko)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Small, round objects</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Apples, eggs, boxes, balls</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三個 (さんこ)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>杯</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">はい (hai)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Cups, glasses, bowls</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Coffee, tea, rice bowls</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三杯 (さんばい)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>回</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">かい (kai)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Times, occurrences</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Once, twice, how many times</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三回 (さんかい)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.3rem;"><strong>階</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">かい (kai)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Building floors</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">1st floor, 3rd floor</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三階 (さんがい)</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div style="background: #eff6ff; border-left: 4px solid #3b82f6; padding: 1rem 1.2rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <strong>🔑 Special Note on 人:</strong> 1 person = ひとり (hitori), 2 people = ふたり (futari). From 3 onward, use the regular pattern: さんにん, よにん, ごにん...
  </div>

  <h2 id="sound-changes">Sound Change Rules — The Tricky Part</h2>
  <p>Certain numbers cause the counter's first consonant to change. This is called <strong>音便 (onbin)</strong> — sound euphony. The main pattern: numbers 1, 3, 6, 8, and 10 often trigger changes with counters starting in h, k, s, or t sounds.</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #dc2626; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Counter</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">1</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">3</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">6</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">8</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">10</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;"><strong>本 (hon)</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">いっ<strong>ぽん</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">さん<strong>ぼん</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ろっ<strong>ぽん</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">はっ<strong>ぽん</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じゅっ<strong>ぽん</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;"><strong>匹 (hiki)</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">いっ<strong>ぴき</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">さん<strong>びき</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ろっ<strong>ぴき</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">はっ<strong>ぴき</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じゅっ<strong>ぴき</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;"><strong>杯 (hai)</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">いっ<strong>ぱい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">さん<strong>ばい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ろっ<strong>ぱい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">はっ<strong>ぱい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じゅっ<strong>ぱい</strong></td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px;"><strong>階 (kai)</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">いっ<strong>かい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">さん<strong>がい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ろっ<strong>かい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">はっ<strong>かい</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じゅっ<strong>かい</strong></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 1rem; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <div style="background: #f0f9ff; border: 1px solid #93c5fd; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>Pattern for h-counters (本, 匹, 杯):</strong>
      <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <li>1, 6, 8, 10 → h becomes <strong>p</strong> (っぽん, っぴき)</li>
        <li>3 → h becomes <strong>b</strong> (さんぼん, さんびき)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div style="background: #fefce8; border: 1px solid #fde68a; padding: 1rem; border-radius: 8px;">
      <strong>Pattern for k-counters (階, 回, 個):</strong>
      <ul style="margin: 0.5rem 0 0; padding-left: 1.2rem; font-size: 0.95rem;">
        <li>1, 6, 8, 10 → add っ (いっかい, ろっかい)</li>
        <li>3 → k may become <strong>g</strong> (さんがい for 階)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 id="time-counters">Time and Date Counters</h2>
  <p>Time expressions use specific counters for hours, minutes, months, and durations:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
    <thead>
      <tr style="background: #059669; color: white;">
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Counter</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Reading</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Used For</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Example</th>
        <th style="padding: 10px; text-align: left;">Watch Out</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>時</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じ (ji)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">O'clock</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三時 (さんじ) = 3 o'clock</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">4時 = よじ, 7時 = しちじ, 9時 = くじ</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>分</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ふん/ぷん (fun/pun)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Minutes</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">五分 (ごふん) = 5 minutes</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">1,3,4,6,8,10 min = ぷん</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>時間</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">じかん (jikan)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Hours (duration)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三時間 (さんじかん) = 3 hours</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Different from 時 (point in time)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>日</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">にち/か (nichi/ka)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Days of month / days</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三日 (みっか) = 3rd / 3 days</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">1st–10th have irregular readings!</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>月</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">がつ (gatsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Months (names)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三月 (さんがつ) = March</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">4月=しがつ, 7月=しちがつ, 9月=くがつ</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>ヶ月</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">かげつ (kagetsu)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Months (duration)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三ヶ月 (さんかげつ) = 3 months</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Different from 月 (month name)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #f8fafc;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>年</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">ねん (nen)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Years</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三年 (さんねん) = 3 years</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Regular — no sound changes</td>
      </tr>
      <tr style="background: #ffffff;">
        <td style="padding: 10px; font-size: 1.2rem;"><strong>週間</strong></td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">しゅうかん (shūkan)</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Weeks</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">三週間 (さんしゅうかん) = 3 weeks</td>
        <td style="padding: 10px;">Regular — no sound changes</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2 id="specialized-counters">Specialized Counters Worth Knowing</h2>
  <p>Beyond the essentials, these counters appear frequently in daily life and JLPT tests:</p>

  <table style="width:100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin: 1.5rem 0;">
